27.34	Small_caps	Small caps	In typography, small capitals (usually abbreviated small caps) are uppercase characters set at the same height and weight as surrounding lowercase (small) letters or text figures. They are used in running text to prevent capitalized words from appearing too large on the page, and as a method of emphasis or distinctiveness for text alongside or instead of italics, or when boldface is inappropriate. For example, TEXT IN CAPS appears as . They can be used to draw attention to the opening phrase or line of a new section of text, or to provide an additional style in a dictionary entry where many parts must be typographically differentiated.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/Small_caps_vs_petite_caps.svg/300px-Small_caps_vs_petite_caps.svg.png
